2:Tb0a,[{"@context":"https://schema.org","@type":"Article","headline":"Best Sunscreen for Florida — What Locals Actually Use | TB Relo","description":"Best sunscreen for Florida living. SPF recommendations for extreme UV, reef-safe picks for beach days, sport formulas, everyday face SPF, and kids options.","url":"https://tbrelo.com/blog/best-sunscreen-florida/","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"Barrett Henry","jobTitle":"REALTOR® & Broker Associate","url":"https://nowtb.com","worksFor":{"@type":"Organization","name":"REMAX Collective"}},"publisher":{"@type":"Organization","name":"TB Relo","url":"https://tbrelo.com"},"datePublished":"2026-04-13","dateModified":"2026-04-13","image":{"@type":"ImageObject","url":"https://tbrelo.com/images/blog/best-sunscreen-florida.jpg"}},{"@context":"https://schema.org","@type":"FAQPage","mainEntity":[{"@type":"Question","name":"How often should I reapply sunscreen in Florida?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Every 2 hours during continuous sun exposure, and immediately after swimming, sweating heavily, or toweling off. Set a phone timer — nobody remembers to reapply without one, and a single application at 9 AM doesn't protect you at noon."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"Do I need sunscreen on cloudy Florida days?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Yes. Up to 80% of UV radiation penetrates cloud cover. Some of the worst sunburns happen on overcast days because people skip protection entirely. If it's light enough outside to see without turning on lights, UV is reaching your skin."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"What's the best sunscreen to keep in my car in Florida?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Mineral sunscreens (zinc oxide) handle heat better than chemical sunscreens when stored in a car. Chemical sunscreen formulas can break down in extreme heat (and your car interior hits 150+ degrees in Florida sun). Blue Lizard Mineral SPF 50 in a car-dedicated bottle is a solid choice."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"Is SPF clothing worth it in Florida?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Absolutely. UPF 50+ sun shirts block 98% of UV without reapplication. They're cooler than you'd expect (moisture-wicking fabric) and eliminate the need for body sunscreen on covered areas. Most serious Florida anglers, kayakers, and golfers wear UPF clothing rather than relying on sunscreen alone."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"When is it safe to go outside without sunscreen in Florida?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"After sunset and before sunrise. That's about it. Even during the winter months (December–February), the UV index in Tampa Bay averages 4–6, which is enough to cause skin damage with prolonged exposure. If you're going to be outside for more than 15 minutes during daylight hours, wear sunscreen."}}]}]5:T3a90,<h2>Florida UV Is No Joke — Here's Why Your Old Sunscreen Won't Cut It</h2>
<p>If you're moving to Florida from a northern state, your relationship with sunscreen is about to change fundamentally. This isn't "put some on for the beach trip" territory anymore. Florida's UV index regularly hits 10–11 (extreme) from April through October, and stays at 6–8 even in winter. For reference, a UV index of 3–5 is considered "moderate" and is typical of a northern summer.</p>
<p>What does that mean practically? Unprotected skin burns in 10–15 minutes during peak hours (10 AM – 4 PM) in a Florida summer. Even on cloudy days, 80% of UV radiation penetrates cloud cover. The sun here is relentless.</p>
<p>After 23+ years in Tampa Bay, I can tell you that Floridians who've been here a while take sun protection seriously — not because they're paranoid, but because they've seen what happens when you don't. Premature aging, sun spots, and skin cancer rates in Florida are among the highest in the country. This guide covers what actually works and what locals use daily.</p>
<h2>SPF Basics for Florida Living</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>SPF 30</strong> is the absolute minimum for Florida. It blocks about 97% of UVB rays.</li>
<li><strong>SPF 50</strong> blocks about 98% and is what most dermatologists in Florida recommend for daily use.</li>
<li><strong>SPF 70–100</strong> offers marginally more protection but gives people a false sense of security — they apply less and reapply less often. SPF 50, applied properly and reapplied every 2 hours, is more effective than SPF 100 applied once.</li>
<li><strong>Broad spectrum</strong> is mandatory. This means the sunscreen blocks both UVA (aging, cancer) and UVB (burning) rays. Check the label.</li>
<li><strong>Water resistant (80 minutes)</strong> is the standard you want for any outdoor activity in Florida — you'll sweat it off otherwise.</li>
</ul>
<h2>Best Everyday Face Sunscreen</h2>
<h3>EltaMD UV Clear Broad-Spectrum SPF 46</h3>
<p><a href="https://www.amazon.com/s?k=EltaMD+UV+Clear+SPF+46+face+sunscreen&#x26;tag=tbrelo-20">EltaMD UV Clear SPF 46 Face Sunscreen</a></p>
<p>This is what Florida dermatologists recommend more than any other face sunscreen. Lightweight, no white cast, doesn't clog pores, and sits beautifully under makeup or on bare skin. It contains niacinamide (good for skin texture) and zinc oxide (physical UV blocker).</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>SPF:</strong> 46 (broad spectrum)</li>
<li><strong>Type:</strong> Chemical + physical hybrid</li>
<li><strong>Feel:</strong> Lightweight, absorbs quickly, no greasy residue</li>
<li><strong>Price:</strong> ~$37 for 1.7 oz (lasts 2–3 months with daily use)</li>
<li><strong>Florida verdict:</strong> The best daily face sunscreen available. Period. Every dermatologist office in Tampa Bay carries it. Yes, it's $37 — your face is worth it.</li>
</ul>
<h3>La Roche-Posay Anthelios Melt-In Sunscreen SPF 60</h3>
<p><a href="https://www.amazon.com/s?k=La+Roche-Posay+Anthelios+Melt-In+sunscreen+SPF+60&#x26;tag=tbrelo-20">La Roche-Posay Anthelios Melt-In SPF 60</a></p>
<p>French pharmacy sunscreen technology that's earned a massive following in Florida. The "melt-in" texture absorbs instantly without the chalky, heavy feeling of most SPF 60 products. Excellent for sensitive skin.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>SPF:</strong> 60 (broad spectrum)</li>
<li><strong>Type:</strong> Chemical</li>
<li><strong>Feel:</strong> Velvety, fast-absorbing</li>
<li><strong>Price:</strong> ~$28–$36 for 3 oz</li>
<li><strong>Florida verdict:</strong> Great for people who hate the feel of sunscreen. You forget you're wearing it within 30 seconds of application. SPF 60 is a nice bonus for Florida's extreme UV days.</li>
</ul>
<h3>CeraVe Hydrating Mineral Sunscreen SPF 50</h3>
<p><a href="https://www.amazon.com/s?k=CeraVe+Hydrating+Mineral+Sunscreen+SPF+50+face&#x26;tag=tbrelo-20">CeraVe Hydrating Mineral Sunscreen SPF 50</a></p>
<p>If you want a mineral (zinc oxide/titanium dioxide) sunscreen at a drugstore price, CeraVe delivers. Mineral sunscreens sit on top of the skin and physically block UV rather than absorbing it. Some people prefer this because it starts working immediately (no 15-minute wait).</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>SPF:</strong> 50 (broad spectrum)</li>
<li><strong>Type:</strong> 100% mineral (zinc oxide, titanium dioxide)</li>
<li><strong>Feel:</strong> Slightly thicker than chemical options; light white cast on darker skin tones</li>
<li><strong>Price:</strong> ~$15 for 2.5 oz</li>
<li><strong>Florida verdict:</strong> Best budget face sunscreen for daily Florida use. The white cast is minimal on lighter skin tones and blends out with a little work on darker tones.</li>
</ul>
<h2>Best Sport / Water-Resistant Sunscreen</h2>
<h3>Neutrogena Beach Defense SPF 70</h3>
<p><a href="https://www.amazon.com/s?k=Neutrogena+Beach+Defense+SPF+70+sunscreen&#x26;tag=tbrelo-20">Neutrogena Beach Defense SPF 70 Sunscreen</a></p>
<p>The workhorse sunscreen for Florida outdoor days. Water resistant for 80 minutes, affordable enough to apply generously (most people don't use enough), and widely available at every Publix and Target in Tampa Bay.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>SPF:</strong> 70 (broad spectrum)</li>
<li><strong>Water resistant:</strong> 80 minutes</li>
<li><strong>Best for:</strong> Beach days, pool time, yard work, outdoor sports</li>
<li><strong>Price:</strong> ~$10–$13 for 6.7 oz</li>
<li><strong>Florida verdict:</strong> This is what I keep in my car, my golf bag, and the garage. The price means you'll actually use enough of it — the biggest sunscreen mistake is applying too little because the bottle was $40.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Coppertone Sport SPF 50 Spray</h3>
<p><a href="https://www.amazon.com/s?k=Coppertone+Sport+SPF+50+spray+sunscreen&#x26;tag=tbrelo-20">Coppertone Sport SPF 50 Spray Sunscreen</a></p>
<p>Spray sunscreens are controversial (people don't apply enough), but for reapplication when you're sweaty and sandy at the beach, they're practical. Coppertone Sport stays on through sweat and water better than most sprays.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>SPF:</strong> 50 (broad spectrum)</li>
<li><strong>Water resistant:</strong> 80 minutes</li>
<li><strong>Best for:</strong> Quick reapplication, hard-to-reach areas (back)</li>
<li><strong>Price:</strong> ~$9–$12 for 5.5 oz</li>
<li><strong>Application tip:</strong> Hold 6 inches from skin, spray generously until skin glistens, then rub in. Spraying from a foot away in the wind means most of it blows off. On the face, spray into your hands first, then apply.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Sun Bum Original SPF 50</h3>
<p><a href="https://www.amazon.com/s?k=Sun+Bum+Original+SPF+50+sunscreen+lotion&#x26;tag=tbrelo-20">Sun Bum Original SPF 50 Lotion Sunscreen</a></p>
<p>The unofficial sunscreen of Florida beach culture. Sun Bum smells like a tropical vacation (banana scent), applies smoothly, and actually delivers strong protection. It's what you'll see in most Florida beach bags.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>SPF:</strong> 50 (broad spectrum)</li>
<li><strong>Water resistant:</strong> 80 minutes</li>
<li><strong>Vegan and cruelty-free:</strong> Yes</li>
<li><strong>Price:</strong> ~$14–$17 for 8 oz</li>
<li><strong>Florida verdict:</strong> If you want sunscreen that doesn't feel or smell clinical, Sun Bum is the answer. Great protection with a beach-culture vibe that makes you more likely to actually wear it.</li>
</ul>
<h2>Reef-Safe Options for Beach Days</h2>
<p>Florida's coral reefs and marine ecosystems are under stress, and oxybenzone and octinoxate (common chemical sunscreen ingredients) are proven to damage coral. If you're heading to the Keys, Siesta Key, or any Florida beach where you'll be in the water, consider reef-safe options.</p>
<h3>Blue Lizard Australian Sunscreen SPF 50+</h3>
<p><a href="https://www.amazon.com/s?k=Blue+Lizard+Australian+Sunscreen+SPF+50+mineral&#x26;tag=tbrelo-20">Blue Lizard Australian Sunscreen SPF 50+</a></p>
<p>Mineral-only formula (zinc oxide) that's genuinely reef-safe — no chemical filters. The bottle cap turns blue in UV light as a reminder to apply. Thick but effective.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>SPF:</strong> 50+ (broad spectrum)</li>
<li><strong>Reef safe:</strong> Yes (mineral only, no oxybenzone or octinoxate)</li>
<li><strong>Water resistant:</strong> 80 minutes</li>
<li><strong>Price:</strong> ~$14–$18 for 5 oz</li>
<li><strong>Trade-off:</strong> Thicker application and more visible white cast than chemical sunscreens. Worth it for reef areas.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Raw Elements Face + Body SPF 30</h3>
<p><a href="https://www.amazon.com/s?k=Raw+Elements+Face+Body+SPF+30+reef+safe+sunscreen&#x26;tag=tbrelo-20">Raw Elements Face and Body SPF 30 Sunscreen</a></p>
<p>A paste-style mineral sunscreen that won't wash off easily — actually a benefit for snorkeling and swimming. It's certified reef-safe by the Haereticus Environmental Lab, which is the strictest certification available.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>SPF:</strong> 30 (broad spectrum)</li>
<li><strong>Reef safe:</strong> Yes (certified by HEL)</li>
<li><strong>Water resistant:</strong> 80 minutes</li>
<li><strong>Price:</strong> ~$18–$22 for 3 oz</li>
<li><strong>Trade-off:</strong> It's thick. You'll look like a lifeguard from the 1980s. But it stays on in the water better than anything else on this list.</li>
</ul>
<h2>Best Sunscreen for Kids</h2>
<h3>Banana Boat Kids Sport SPF 50</h3>
<p><a href="https://www.amazon.com/s?k=Banana+Boat+Kids+Sport+SPF+50+sunscreen&#x26;tag=tbrelo-20">Banana Boat Kids Sport SPF 50 Sunscreen Lotion</a></p>
<p>Tear-free formula that stays on through swimming and sweat. The lotion applies easier than sprays on squirmy kids, and the SPF 50 is right in the sweet spot for Florida UV.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>SPF:</strong> 50 (broad spectrum)</li>
<li><strong>Water resistant:</strong> 80 minutes</li>
<li><strong>Tear-free:</strong> Yes</li>
<li><strong>Price:</strong> ~$8–$10 for 6 oz</li>
<li><strong>Florida note:</strong> Keep a bottle in every car, every bag, and at the front door. Florida kids are outside year-round, and the best sunscreen is the one that's within arm's reach when they run out the door.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Thinkbaby Safe Sunscreen SPF 50+</h3>
<p><a href="https://www.amazon.com/s?k=Thinkbaby+Safe+Sunscreen+SPF+50&#x26;tag=tbrelo-20">Thinkbaby Safe Sunscreen SPF 50+</a></p>
<p>Mineral (zinc oxide) formula with no harmful chemicals — parents who are concerned about chemical sunscreen ingredients use this. It's the first sunscreen to pass Whole Foods' strictest safety requirements.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>SPF:</strong> 50+ (broad spectrum)</li>
<li><strong>Type:</strong> Mineral (zinc oxide)</li>
<li><strong>Water resistant:</strong> 80 minutes</li>
<li><strong>Price:</strong> ~$12–$16 for 3 oz</li>
<li><strong>Florida note:</strong> Best for babies and toddlers. The mineral formula is gentle on sensitive skin. White cast is noticeable but who cares — your kid is protected.</li>
</ul>
<h2>Don't Waste Money On These</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>SPF lip balm under 30</strong> — Your lips burn and blister faster than any other skin. Get <a href="https://www.amazon.com/s?k=SPF+50+lip+balm+sun+protection&#x26;tag=tbrelo-20">SPF 50 lip balm</a> and keep it with you. Sun Bum and Neutrogena both make good options.</li>
<li><strong>SPF moisturizers as your only protection</strong> — SPF 15 in your morning moisturizer is not enough for Florida. It's a light base layer at best. Apply real sunscreen on top.</li>
<li><strong>Expired sunscreen</strong> — sunscreen expires, and the active ingredients break down. Check dates, especially if you brought a half-used bottle from up north that's been sitting in a drawer for two years.</li>
<li><strong>Indoor tanning as "base tan protection"</strong> — this is a myth. A base tan provides roughly SPF 3 of protection. That's meaningless in Florida's UV 11 summer.</li>
</ul>
<h2>Cost Comparison — What Does a Year of Florida Sunscreen Cost?</h2>
<p>Being realistic about Florida sunscreen usage:</p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Product</th>
<th>Use Case</th>
<th>Bottles/Year</th>
<th>Cost/Year</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>EltaMD UV Clear (face)</td>
<td>Daily</td>
<td>4–5</td>
<td>$150–$185</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Neutrogena Beach Defense (body)</td>
<td>Weekends/outdoor</td>
<td>6–8</td>
<td>$60–$100</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Sun Bum (beach/pool days)</td>
<td>Monthly beach trips</td>
<td>3–4</td>
<td>$42–$68</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Kids formula</td>
<td>Year-round</td>
<td>8–12</td>
<td>$64–$120</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><strong>Total (adult, no kids)</strong></td>
<td></td>
<td></td>
<td><strong>$210–$285</strong></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><strong>Total (family of 4)</strong></td>
<td></td>
<td></td>
<td><strong>$350–$475</strong></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p>That's roughly $20–$40/month for comprehensive sun protection. Compare that to one dermatologist visit for a suspicious mole ($200+ with biopsy) or a skin cancer treatment ($5,000–$20,000+), and sunscreen is the cheapest insurance you'll ever buy.</p>
<h2>FAQ</h2>
<h3>How often should I reapply sunscreen in Florida?</h3>
<p>Every 2 hours during continuous sun exposure, and immediately after swimming, sweating heavily, or toweling off. Set a phone timer — nobody remembers to reapply without one, and a single application at 9 AM doesn't protect you at noon.</p>
<h3>Do I need sunscreen on cloudy Florida days?</h3>
<p>Yes. Up to 80% of UV radiation penetrates cloud cover. Some of the worst sunburns happen on overcast days because people skip protection entirely. If it's light enough outside to see without turning on lights, UV is reaching your skin.</p>
<h3>What's the best sunscreen to keep in my car in Florida?</h3>
<p>Mineral sunscreens (zinc oxide) handle heat better than chemical sunscreens when stored in a car. Chemical sunscreen formulas can break down in extreme heat (and your car interior hits 150+ degrees in Florida sun). <a href="https://www.amazon.com/s?k=Blue+Lizard+mineral+sunscreen+SPF+50&#x26;tag=tbrelo-20">Blue Lizard Mineral SPF 50</a> in a car-dedicated bottle is a solid choice.</p>
<h3>Is SPF clothing worth it in Florida?</h3>
<p>Absolutely. <a href="https://www.amazon.com/s?k=UPF+50+sun+protection+shirt+long+sleeve&#x26;tag=tbrelo-20">UPF 50+ sun shirts</a> block 98% of UV without reapplication. They're cooler than you'd expect (moisture-wicking fabric) and eliminate the need for body sunscreen on covered areas. Most serious Florida anglers, kayakers, and golfers wear UPF clothing rather than relying on sunscreen alone.</p>
<h3>When is it safe to go outside without sunscreen in Florida?</h3>
<p>After sunset and before sunrise. That's about it. Even during the winter months (December–February), the UV index in Tampa Bay averages 4–6, which is enough to cause skin damage with prolonged exposure. If you're going to be outside for more than 15 minutes during daylight hours, wear sunscreen.</p>
